Web Hosting – Planning Phase
Web Serving Stack

My web server will run Apache HTTP Server to host two websites.
Apache will serve both sites using virtual hosts, allowing multiple websites to run from the same server.

Ports
Inbound Ports

The following ports must be open inbound to allow users to access the websites.

Port	Protocol	Source	Purpose
80	HTTP	Anywhere (0.0.0.0/0)	Allows normal web traffic
443	HTTPS	Anywhere (0.0.0.0/0)	Allows encrypted web traffic
22	SSH	Trusted IP only	Allows administrators to manage the server

Port 80 will allow users to reach the website using HTTP, and port 443 will allow secure HTTPS connections.

SSH access will be restricted to trusted IP addresses for security.

Outbound Ports
Port	Destination	Purpose
80	Internet	Download packages and updates
443	Internet	Secure downloads, APIs, certificates
53	DNS Servers	Domain name resolution

Outbound traffic allows the server to install updates, access DNS servers, and communicate with external services.

Firewall Levels

Firewall rules will be configured at multiple levels.

Network ACL (NACL)

NACL rules will allow inbound and outbound traffic for:

HTTP (80)

HTTPS (443)

SSH (22)

These rules apply at the subnet level.

Security Group (SG)

Security groups will allow:

Port	Source
22	Admin IP
80	0.0.0.0/0
443	0.0.0.0/0

Security groups act as the primary firewall for the EC2 instance.

System Firewall

On the server itself I may use UFW or iptables to further restrict traffic.

Example rules:

Allow:

SSH
HTTP
HTTPS

Block everything else.

Configuration
Files that need to be edited

The main Apache configuration files are:

/etc/apache2/apache2.conf
/etc/apache2/ports.conf
/etc/apache2/sites-available/

Virtual host files will be placed in:

/etc/apache2/sites-available/
Configuring Apache

Apache will be configured by:

Creating virtual host configuration files

Enabling those sites

Restarting the Apache service

Example commands:

a2ensite example.conf
systemctl restart apache2
Virtual Hosts

Two virtual hosts will be created for the two websites.

Example:

/etc/apache2/sites-available/site1.conf
/etc/apache2/sites-available/site2.conf

Each virtual host will define:

ServerName

DocumentRoot

Logging location

This allows both websites to run from the same Apache server.

DNS and Host Configuration

If DNS records are available, each domain will point to the server's public IP address.

Example:

site1.example.com -> server IP
site2.example.com -> server IP

If testing locally, entries may be added to:

/etc/hosts
SSL / TLS (Stretch Goal)
Creating a Self-Signed Certificate

A self-signed certificate can be created with OpenSSL:
openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 -keyout server.key -out server.crt
Certificate Storage

Certificates should be stored in:
/etc/ssl/certs
/etc/ssl/private

This is the standard location for SSL files on Linux systems.
The private key must be protected because it proves server identity.

Certificate Permissions
Private key:
600
Certificate file:
644

Only root should have access to the private key.
Certificate Authority Validation

If using a real certificate authority:
Domain Validation (DV) is usually sufficient for most websites
Organization Validation (OV) verifies the organization

Extended Validation (EV) provides the highest trust level but is rarely required
For most use cases, Domain Validation is appropriate.
Enabling HTTPS
Apache must enable the SSL module.

Example command:
a2enmod ssl
A new virtual host must be created for HTTPS:

<VirtualHost *:443>

This will include:
SSL certificate path
SSL key path
Redirect HTTP to HTTPS

This ensures all users connect securely.

Logging

Apache logs are stored in:
/var/log/apache2/
Common logs:

access.log
error.log
Logs can be viewed using:

tail -f /var/log/apache2/access.log
This helps troubleshoot issues with the website.

Controlling the Web Server
Apache runs as a system service.

Commands:

Start service:
systemctl start apache2

Stop service:
systemctl stop apache2

Restart service:
systemctl restart apache2

Check status:

systemctl status apache2
Web Content Location

The default Apache web directory is:
/var/www/

Each site will have its own folder.
Example structure:

/var/www/
    site1/
        index.html
    site2/
        index.html

Each virtual host will point to its specific directory.
User and Permissions

Apache runs as the user:
www-data

This means the web server reads files as the www-data user.
File Permissions

Typical permissions:
Directories:
755
Files:
644

This allows Apache to read files but prevents unauthorized modification.
Developer Access

Developers will update website content using SFTP.
SFTP is preferred because:
encrypted connection
uses SSH authentication
more secure than FTP
Developers will be given access to the content directories.

Example group:
webdev
Developers will have write permission to their website directories but not system files.

Summary
This setup will allow the server to:
host two websites using Apache virtual hosts
support HTTP and HTTPS
maintain secure firewall rules
allow developers to update content using SFTP
log server activity for troubleshooting
use SSL certificates for encrypted communication